The paper deals with approximation algorithms for geometric problems involving planar arrangements of lines and points, which suggests that it belongs to the computational geometry (cs.CG) sub-category. The use of approximation algorithms and the focus on optimization problems involving distances and metrics also suggests that it could belong to the data structures (cs.DS) and discrete mathematics (cs.DM) sub-categories. The mention of subquadratic approximation algorithms and applications to matching, clustering, and nearest-neighbor problems suggests that it could also belong to the numerical analysis (cs.NA) and artificial intelligence (cs.AI) sub-categories.
